With bs4 4.7.1 + you can use `:contains` and `:has` to isolate based on `WORD` being in element with a given class within a table. In the case you describe you could also work `:contains` direct off `table` i.e. `table = soup.select_one(&#39;table:contains(&quot;WORD&quot;)&#39;)` .

    from bs4 import BeautifulSoup as bs
    
    html = &#39;&#39;&#39;
    &lt;html&gt;
     &lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;
     &lt;body&gt;
      &lt;table&gt; 
       &lt;tbody&gt;
        &lt;tr&gt; 
         &lt;td class=&quot;someclass1&quot;&gt;WORD&lt;/td&gt; 
        &lt;/tr&gt; 
       &lt;/tbody&gt;
      &lt;/table&gt;
      &lt;table&gt;&lt;/table&gt; 
      &lt;table&gt; 
       &lt;tbody&gt;
        &lt;tr&gt; 
         &lt;td class=&quot;someclass1&quot;&gt;NOT_WORD&lt;/td&gt; 
        &lt;/tr&gt; 
       &lt;/tbody&gt;
      &lt;/table&gt;
      &lt;table&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
     &lt;/body&gt;
    &lt;/html&gt;
    &#39;&#39;&#39;
    soup = bs(html, &#39;lxml&#39;)
    table = soup.select_one(&#39;table:has(.someclass1:contains(&quot;WORD&quot;))&#39;)
    print(table.text)

